Tropicana complies with CalOSHA?s Process Safety Management (PSM) standards (Title 8 CCR Section 5189), incorporating technology, procedures, and management practices into a comprehensive program that effectively minimizes the potential for hazardous chemical releases.  In addition to mitigation systems (automatic shut-off valves, high pressure relief valves, level alarms, barricades, monitoring/detection systems) engineered into the refrigeration system, Tropicana promotes safety in the operation of the ammonia system, by the following PSM program elements:

?Involving employees in various aspects of program development and implementation;
?Maintenance of updated process information, accessible to all employees;
?Completion of a process hazard analysis (PHA) that identifies any hazards associated with deviation from normal operating conditions;
?Development and implementation of standard operating procedures (SOPs);
?Use of safe work practices in all aspects of process operation;
?Personnel training;
?Contractor safety program;
?Pre-startup safety reviews prior to introduction of ammonia into the system;
?Comprehensive inspection and maintenance program;
?In-depth reviews of any significant changes in the ammonia system; 
?Investigation of any accidents or ?near misses,? identifying any modifications that could prevent similar incidents in the future;
?Internal audits, identifying any areas of program noncompliance and corrective actions required.
There have been no accidents in the last five years, or in the history of the Tropicana, City of Industry facility, from the ammonia refrigeration system that have resulted in deaths, injuries, or significant property damage on-site; or, off-site deaths, injuries, evacuation, sheltering in place, property damage, or environmental damage.  

